<HEAD>Latest Developments in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at major developments in Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ROMANIA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav traveler reports two people were killed during
weekend demonstrations against hard-line President Nicolae
Ceausescu, the largest anti-government demonstrations in two years.
   The country closes its border with Yugolavia to all but official
traffic, and security is reported tightened at the Hungarian border
following reports of violent weekend demonstrations.
   Hungarian legislators report tanks patrolling the major Romanian
city of Timisoara and nearby Arad, the sites of demonstrations.
Romanian emigres report further unrest in the city of Brasov, site
of a major uprising in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief, Karel Urbanek, is quoted as saying
his party will probably try to form a coalition with other leftist
parties before free elections planned next year.
   The party daily, Rude Pravo, prints a front-page apology for
previous articles that attacked such reformers as Vaclav Havel and
Alexander Dubcek.
   Foreign Minister Jiri Dienstbier prepares to travel to Moscow on
