<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-89 1919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouse-Pamphlets     12-18 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Pamphlets,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaflet Regulation Declared Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday declared
unconstitutional a 1976 regulation barring people from passing out
leaflets in an area around the White House.
   U.S. District Court Judge John Pratt issued the ruling in the
case of a Carol Ann Fennelly, charged with illegally distributing
pamphlets June 21 along East Executive Avenue between the White
House and Treasury Department.
   The material urged passers-by to write members of Congress in
favor of housing for the homeless.
   The judge said the regulation is an unconstitutional limitation
on First Amendment rights.
   National Park Service regulations approved in 1970 were part of
an effort to protect White House security by restrictions on
demonstrations. The 1976 amendments were drafted to preserve an
atmosphere of calm and tranquility at memorials and buildings
associated with past presidents.
   In 1976, ``nothing was said about the underlying purpose of
presidential security which was the overriding purpose of the
comprehensive regulations issued in 1970,'' Pratt said. The 1970
regulation allowed distribution of pamphlets and leaflets by not
mentioning them.
   ``In contrast, the 1976 revision ... for the first time banned''
distribution of material in the White House Park area, the judge
said.
   Pratt noted that Fennelly ``would violate the regulation by
passing out a leaflet,'' but ``could convey the same identical
message by word of mouth without fear of arrest.''
   ``A ban on the free distribution of leaflets and pamphlets in
those remote areas far removed from the White House itself has no
conceivable governmental interest,'' Pratt said in his opinion.
   ``It's distressing that the government continues to try to
impose these ridiculous limitations on free speech in the nation's
capital,'' said American Civil Liberties Union lawyer Arthur
Spitzer, who handled the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891218-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-89 1921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Rushdie     12-18 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushdie,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Four Iranians Suspected of Being Rushdie `Hit Squad'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Iranians being held by police
under the Prevention of Terrorism Act believe they are suspected of
plotting to kill author Salman Rushdie, their lawyer said Monday.
   The three students and a disabled father of four were arrested
Friday at their homes in Manchester, police said. Under the act,
suspects can be held seven days without charge.
   ``The police have told me very little, but the men are under the
impression they have been arrested because they are suspected of
being a hit squad to kill Salman Rushdie,'' attorney Zahir Aziz
said.
   Moslems worldwide have mounted protests against the British
author and his novel, ``The Satanic Verses.'' The Indian-born
Rushdie was condemned to death Feb. 14 by the late Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who accused him of blaspheming Islam
in his novel.
   Rushdie has been in hiding ever since under police protection.
   Friday's arrests put in jeopardy tentative steps to improve
Anglo-Iranian relations and restore diplomatic links severed over
the Rushdie affair.
   The detainees' lawyer identified the students as Karen Abrinia,
32; Mehrdad Kokabi, 33; and Hussein Gharibi. No age was immediately
available for Gharibi.
   The attorney asked that the fourth man, 40-year-old Javad
Mousavi, who suffers from multiple sclerosis, be moved from his
police cell to a hospital.
   A Manchester police spokeswoman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, refused to say why the suspects were detained.
   However, she said the detentions were not connected to the U.S.
State Department's warning last week of a possible terrorist attack
on a U.S. target in Western Europe or West Africa.
   Patrick Stephenson, registrar at the University of Manchester
Institute of Science and Technology, said Kokabi and Abrinia were
engineering students who had completed their course work for doctor
of philosophy degrees and were writing dissertations. It was not
known where Gharibi studies.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency on Friday quoted
the Iranian newspaper Kayhan as saying the arrests followed
demonstrations by Moslems in more than 1,000 mosques throughout
Britain against Rushdie.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said police
activity in Manchester is believed to have intensified following a
stormy meeting there on Oct. 21 to celebrate the birthday of the
Islamic prophet Mohammed. At that session, hard-line Moslems voted
overwhelmingly to support the call for Rushdie's execution.
   Kayhan was quoted as saying police broke into the homes of the
four Iranians ``without producing any legal warrants, and, after
the unauthorized search of their homes, forcibly took them into
custody.''
   The Manchester police spokeswoman refused to comment when asked
about the warrants.
   English-born Dawn Mousavi said police came to the family's home
in Manchester on Friday afternoon and arrested her husband.
   ``We were kept in the kitchen for two hours while the police
searched the house. They took away personal papers like letters and
even bank books. They turned everything upside down and took the
floorboards up,'' she said.
   ``Javad is innocent. I don't know why he is detained. He is not
a politically active person _ although we both support the Iranian
government,'' Mrs. Mousavi said.
</TEXT>
