<FIRST>u a AM-LaughingTrial     12-18 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laughing Trial,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mohawk Casino Owner Pleads Guilty to Federal Gambling Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of an illegal casino on a Mohawk
Indian reservation pleaded guilty to gambling charges on the first
day of his federal trial Monday, saying he made the plea so he
could appeal.
   ``In order to take this case to the next level, I had to make a
plea, no matter how much I feel I'm innocent,'' Anthony Laughing
said outside the courtroom.
   Laughing, a 42-year-old Mohawk, pleaded guilty to single counts
of possession of slot machines, operating an illegal gambling
business and resisting arrest. Under a plea bargain, prosecutors
dropped six other counts.
   The plea came after a 90-minute conference that followed
Assistant U.S. Attorney John Brunetti's opening argument in the
trial.
   Laughing is to be sentenced Feb. 27. He faces up to 10 years in
prison if given the maximum penalties for each of the three counts.
   He entered conditional pleas to the gambling charges, reserving
the right to appeal the charges on the basis of Indian sovereignty
issues.
   Laughing and 12 other Mohawks who were arrested in a July 20
raid by state and federal law enforcement officers contend the St.
Regis Indian Reservation is a sovereign nation and that state and
federal laws do not apply there.
   Laughing said he wanted to get his case to the next federal
level more quickly rather than endure an extended trial. ``I am
innocent and if I have to appeal this all the way to the Supreme
Court, I will,'' he said.
   His attorney, Michael Vavonese, said an appeal would be filed
with the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York City after
sentencing.
   Laughing also said he did not believe he would receive a fair
trial before U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn because McCurn has
ruled repeatedly in the government's favor.
   McCurn earlier this year rejected the sovereignty argument in
pretrial motions, citing other Indian cases where courts have ruled
that federal and state governments have jurisdiction on Indian
reservations.
   McCurn allowed Laughing to remain free on $300,000 bail, but
continued a U.S. magistrate's order that he report to authorities
twice daily and be at home overnight to receive a call from them.
   Laughing owns Tony's Vegas International, the largest of seven
high-stakes casinos on the reservation, which straddles the
U.S.-Canadian border in northern New York.
   He avoided arrest in the July 20 raid, and was a fugitive for
two months until being caught Sept. 21 after a chase by state
troopers.
   Laughing's case is the fifth to be resolved. Three other Mohawks
have either been convicted or pleaded guilty to gambling charges. A
fifth Mohawk was acquitted when prosecutors failed to prove he was
the owner of a truck stop where state police seized slot machines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891218-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cuba     12-18 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba,1st Ld-Writethru,a0589,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Calls Cuba a ``Renegade Nation''</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 9 grafs, State Department comment on terrorism and Cuban
view; Add byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department renewed its criticism on
Monday of Cuban arms shipments to Central America and said ``it is
time for Cuba to stop acting like a renegade nation.''
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Cuba should stop
sending weapons to Nicaragua's leftist government and Nicaragua
should stop sending such arms on to Salvadoran rebels.
   She said that Cuba must begin shouldering more responsibility
than before because it will soon become a member of the U.N.
Security Council.
   ``It needs now to begin acting in a way consistent with the
great responsibility it will bear in the council,'' she said.
   Her statement suggested a shift in emphasis about the U.S. view
of who is to blame for the continuing upheaval in Central America.
   The administration previously had said the Soviet Union had a
duty to persuade Cuba and Nicaragua to block the transfer of Soviet
bloc weapons to the Salvadoran insurgency.
   In her remarks on Monday, Ms. Tutwiler seemed to play down
Soviet responsibility for the continuing violence in Central
America. But, under questioning, she said that the administration
has not backed away from its previous view and that Central America
continues to be a divisive issue for Moscow and Washington.
   The administration does not challenge Moscow's contention that
it has ceased direct arms deliveries to Central America. But
officials say they are convinced that some Soviet weapons arrive in
Central America via third countries, especially Cuba.
   Monday evening, in response to a press question, the State
Department said that Cuba continues to be one of six countries on a
U.S. government list of countries that support international
terrorism.
   ``Cuba continues to provide safe haven, weapons and political
and financial support to a wide range of leftist and insurgent
organizations that use terrorism,'' the department said.
   It said Cuba supports a Colombian leftist group that has
attacked western economic interests.
   In addition, it said that the Salvadoran rebel group backed by
Cuba has publicly threatened Americans assisting the Salvadoran
government as ``legitimate targets of assassination.''
   Also, Cuba has supported a leftist group in Chile believed
responsible for several international terrorist incidents in recent
years, the department said.
   Joining Cuba on the State Department terrorism list are Iran,
Syria, Libya, South Yemen and North Korea.
   Cuba, in turn, regards the United States as the country most
prone to international adventurism worldwide. It has cited repeated
U.S.-sponsored assassination attempts against President Fidel
Castro and large-scale American military involvement in Central
America.
   Castro recently accused the United States of directly
intervening in the internal affairs of the Philippines by lending
air support to President Corazon Aquino during the recent coup
attempt.
   Beyond that, Castro said that the worldwide U.S. network of
military bases gives the United States the capability to intervene
in virtually any region on short notice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891218-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-89 1936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Shevardnadze 1stLd-Writethru a0626 12-18 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shevardnadze, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Signs Major Agreement to Expand European Trade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 7 grafs SUB for 5th graf, He said ... UPDATING with banquet,
quotes. Picks up 6th, `French Foreign ... with minor editing to trim, conform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze signed a far-reaching trade agreement with the
European Community on Monday, a major step toward getting needed
Western help for his nation's ailing economy.
   On Tuesday, Shevardnadze will pay an unprecedented visit to the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, the center of the Western
military alliance.
   He called the 10-year accord _ the first between Moscow and the
12-nation trading bloc _ ``truly innovative.''
   ``Its nature reflects the dynamism of the process of renewal in
Europe,'' he said.
   He later had what was described as a relaxed dinner with the 12
EC foreign ministers. ``He was like a colleague we have known for
many years,'' said Belgium's foreign minister, Mark Eyskens.
   Hans van den Broek, the Dutch minister, said Shevardnadze
discussed the upheaval in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union's own
economic reform program, among other issues.
   ``His message was: `We do not deny the (economic) situation is
difficult, but grant us more time,''' Van den Broek said.
   On Eastern Europe, ``he was so far as to say that had the
reforms occurred a few years ago, it could have happened with fewer
shocks,'' he added.
   Van den Broek said Shevardnadze lauded Western leaders for
insisting that change must come in Europe but not at the expense of
stability. West German sources said the same point was made at a
separate meeting Shevardnadze had with Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany.
   The Soviet minister said the trade and economic cooperation
agreement he signed at a ceremony at EC headquarters would help
overcome the division of the European continent.
   He said it ``gives food for collective thinking'' about creating
an ``economic complex on our Continent.''
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, whose country holds the
community's rotating presidency, hailed the arrangement as
``facilitating the integration of the Soviet Union into the world
economy.''
   Frans Andriessen, the community's top-ranking trade official,
cautioned that the pact's success depended on Soviet efforts to
achieve a more market-oriented economy.
   The agreement will gradually get rid of most import quotas on
agricultural and industrial products from the Soviet Union and set
out closer cooperation in areas including nuclear energy and
safety, financial services, environmental protection and management
training.
   In return, the Kremlin has promised to give Western European
businesses greater access to its potentially enormous consumer
market.
   ``Now the agreement is to be put into practice,'' Shevardnadze
said. ``We are ready for it and we intend to continue to work in
earnest, keeping up the high tempo and the spirit of creative
cooperation.''
   He said he did not request the meeting with NATO
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner, but ``simply raised the
question'' of whether there would be a chance to visit the alliance.
   ``We have to take the first step even if the fleets are facing
each other,'' he said.
   He said he had ``no particular hidden thoughts visiting NATO.''
   Questioned about whether the Kremlin intended to join the
Western alliance, he joked he would take a look Tuesday and
``decide whether it's worth joining up now.''
   He made a pitch for dismantling the Western group of 17 nations
formed to keep sensitive technology out of the hands of the East
bloc nations. But he said easing its restrictions was up to the
United States, the key partner in the Western drive.
   The accord is the fourth the community has negotiated with
Eastern European countries since it established in June 1988 formal
ties with the socialist economic bloc, the Council for Mutual
Economic Assistance.
   The community has trade and economic cooperation accords with
Poland and Hungary and a smaller one with Czechoslovakia. It is
discussing pacts with Bulgaria and East Germany.
   The Soviet Union imported about $11 billion in goods from the
community in 1987, while the trading bloc bought nearly $16 billion
from Moscow. Total trade between the community and Eastern Europe
amounted to about $56 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
