England on Friday announced projected increases in its loan-loss
reserve and non-performing assets.
   In the past couple of weeks, Wall Street has been devoting
increased concern to the soft real estate market in many parts of
the country and the problems real-estate debt might pose should
prices of properties lag for an extended period.
   Bank of New England shares led the active list, unchanged at 9
on the heels of a 3]-point drop Friday.
   Among other actively traded banking and mortgage issues, Bank of
Boston lost | to 16{ and Federal National Mortgage was down \ at
33{.
   Otherwise, analysts said hopes persisted that stocks could
overcome their recent hesitancy and gain ground in the next few
weeks, aided by the lifting of pressures from yearend tax selling.
   Marriott rose \ to 34~. The company announced a restructuring
plan that calls for its departure from the fast-food and family
restaurant business and the buyback of an additional 10 million of
its shares.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.12 to 193.57. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off .52 at 374.98.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 14.08 to
2,739.55, reducing its gain for the week to 8.11 points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 3 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 616 up, 897 down and 481 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 240.39 million shares, against 178.70
million in the previous session.
